Description: A sealing for an unknown object, probably a document, retaining the impression of a piece of cord, perhaps of palm-fibre: a single strand of fibre is embedded nearby. Two oval impressions from the same engraved gem survive, with Harpokrates, holding a cornucopia, seated to left on the back of a sphinx to right. Unfired pale yellow-brown mud.
Curator's comments: Terracotta IV Donated: Egypt Exploration Society. Roman, probably second century AD. Compare coins of Trajan with similar figure-type: Poole 1892: pl. xvii:460; Bakhoum 1999: pl. viii:4, terracotta figure: Schmidt 2003: 278, fig. 13.
Bibliographic references: Terracotta / Catalogue of Terracottas in the British Museum (3637)
